        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Microsoft faces the heat</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">In the early 1990s, Microsoft was riding high, dominating the personal computer market. Founder Bill Gates had his eyes on <strong>everything from operating systems to software, peripherals, and even book publishing</strong>. Some insiders whispered that Microsoft was trying to be the IBM of software. But where there’s smoke, there’s usually a regulatory fire.
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bill-gates-1998-senate-hearing-microsoft-antitrust-case.png" alt="In 1998, Gates was called before the Senate Judiciary Committee to be questioned about Microsoft's dominance in the software market" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
In 1998, Gates was called before the Senate Judiciary Committee to be questioned about Microsoft's dominance in the software market. Credits: JESSICA PERSSON/AFP via Getty Images</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">That fire started when the US Department of Justice (DOJ) had a renewed interest in the <strong>antitrust case that the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) had closed</strong>. In 1998, the DOJ filed a <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-26-04-2025-landmark-antitrust-lawsuit?source=website" target="_blank">landmark antitrust lawsuit</a>, accusing Microsoft of abusing its monopoly power, especially by bundling its Internet Explorer browser with its Windows operating system.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The question at the heart of the case was simple. <strong>Could Microsoft legally bundle Internet Explorer with Windows?</strong> The answer, however, wasn’t so simple. The government argued that Microsoft’s bundling stifled competition by making it deliberately difficult for consumers to install rival browsers like Netscape Navigator or Opera. After all, if every PC came preloaded with Internet Explorer, why bother downloading something else?
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>


