    <mj-column>
      <mj-spacer height="14px" />
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Then came the drama
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>The government accused Microsoft of tweaking its application programming interfaces to give Internet Explorer an unfair advantage</strong> and of strong-arming original equipment manufacturers with restrictive licensing agreements. The company asserted that its browser and Windows had become so intertwined that they were essentially one product. Additionally, it was advantageous for consumers who were getting a browser bundled. 
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Critics pointed out that Internet Explorer wasn’t truly complimentary, since its development and advertising expenses were folded into the fees of Windows. They argued that <strong>if the browser could exist as a standalone app for Mac OS, it should also exist for Windows</strong>. Meanwhile, damning emails, dramatic testimony from Intel executives, and words about wanting to shutdown “Netscape’s air supply” painted a much less innocent picture of Bill Gates.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>Microsoft hurt its case by submitting misleading videos</strong> as evidence that even Microsoft executives admitted were deceptive. Outside the courtroom, Microsoft tried to rally public support. A full-page ad in major newspapers called an <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-26-04-2025-open-letter-to-president-clinton?source=website" target="_blank">“Open Letter to President Clinton”</a> from 240 economists argued that the antitrust law was nothing more than protectionism. Meanwhile, <strong>the public supported Microsoft</strong>, saying Windows may not have been the superior product, but it was convenient, compatible, and could run on almost any machine.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Ctrl + Alt + Regulate</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">To truly understand the case, you have to understand antitrust law. The <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-26-04-2025-sherman-antitrust-act?source=website" target="_blank">Sherman Antitrust Act</a> of 1890 was created to prevent companies from eliminating competition and cornering markets. When monopolies take over, they kill innovation, raise fees, and lower quality. And when competitors fall, so does the motivation to make better products. <strong>In other words, competition keeps businesses from playing dirty, and antitrust laws are the referee</strong>.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/mark-zuckerberg-meta-antitrust-trial.png" alt="Meta CEO Mark Zuckerberg took the witness stand on Monday amid a landmark antitrust trial against the company" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
           <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
Meta CEO Mark Zuckerberg took the witness stand on Monday amid a landmark antitrust hearing against the company. Credits: Anna Moneymaker/Getty Images
</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Ultimately, the Judges presiding over the case <strong>ruled that Microsoft should be split into two companies, one for Windows and another for everything else</strong>. But that didn’t happen. <strong>The case was settled on appeal</strong>, with Microsoft agreeing to change some business practices and share its data with third parties.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The lawsuit made headlines and continues to shape the tech industry to this day. <strong>It created a more favorable and competitive environment, paving the way for the rise of Google, Apple, and countless others</strong>. The US v. Microsoft case still looms large over Silicon Valley. It rattled one giant and rewrote the playbook. It set the stage for other antitrust battles, including <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-26-04-2025-google?source=website" target="_blank">Google</a> and <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-26-04-2025-meta?source=website" target="_blank">Meta</a>, and helped define how the law keeps Big Tech in control.</p>
          </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
